Try using just a regular, 1-dimensional _array_.

Here is an example.\
It&#39;s not exact, and is just a demonstration.

The values _m_ and _n_ are the _rows_ and _columns_, respectively.\
And, I&#39;ll use _0_ to represent an empty space.

The _move_ parameters, _m_ and _n_, will be the coordinate of the piece you&#39;d like to shift, and _z_ will be the amount of places to shift by.

Start by translating _m_ and _n_ to the indice, _i_, of _d_.\
Traverse _d_, starting at _i &amp;plus; 1_, and for every empty space, increase _k_ until _k = z_.\
Following the traversal, deduct _1_ from _j_, if _j = d.length_.\
Proceed with another traversal, shifting all values, starting at _j_, to the right, by _k_.

```java
class Grid {
    int m, n, d[];

    Grid(int m, int n) {
        d = new int[(this.m = m) * (this.n = n)];
    }

    void move(int m, int n, int z) {
        int i = (m * this.n) + n, j, k, l;
        for (j = i + 1, k = 0; j &lt; d.length; j++)
            if (d[j] == 0 &amp;&amp; ++k == z) break;
        if (j == d.length) j--;
        for (l = j; l &gt;= i; l--)
            if (l - k &gt;= i) d[l] = d[l - k];
            else d[l] = 0;
    }

    @Override
    public String toString() {
        StringBuilder s = new StringBuilder();
        Formatter f = new Formatter(s);
        for (int i = 0, t, n = d.length; i &lt; n; i++) {
            if (i != 0 &amp;&amp; i % this.n == 0) f.format(&quot;%n&quot;);
            if ((t = d[i]) == 0) f.format(&quot; . &quot;);
            else f.format(&quot;% d &quot;, t);
        }
        f.flush();
        return s.toString();
    }
}
```

